## 3. Social Problems Caused by Data Center Power Consumption

### 3.1 Environmental Impact and Carbon Footprint

Data centers contribute significantly to greenhouse gas emissions due to their heavy reliance on electricity generated from fossil fuels such as coal and natural gas. Coal-fired power plants, in particular, emit large amounts of carbon dioxide (CO2), a major driver of global warming ([Johnson, 2017](https://www.coursebb.com/2017/01/25/business-social-problems-data-center-power-consumption-cause/)). Nuclear power, while cleaner in terms of CO2 emissions, produces highly toxic and radioactive waste that poses long-term environmental challenges.

The carbon footprint of data centers is substantial, with estimates suggesting they account for around 3% of global emissions, which is 50% more than the entire airline industry ([ENGIE Impact, n.d.](https://www.engieimpact.com/who-we-serve/data-centers)). This environmental burden is expected to grow as the number of internet-connected devices increases exponentially—from 12 billion in recent years to an estimated 100 billion by 2025 ([ENGIE Impact, n.d.](https://www.engieimpact.com/who-we-serve/data-centers)).

### 3.2 Resource Depletion and Water Usage

Beyond electricity, data centers also consume significant amounts of water for cooling purposes, which can strain local water resources, especially in water-scarce regions ([Dgtlinfra, n.d.](https://dgtlinfra.com/how-data-centers-impact-the-environment/)). This raises social concerns about the sustainability of data center operations and their impact on community resources.

### 3.3 Health and Community Implications

The environmental effects of data center power consumption extend to public health. Emissions from coal plants contribute to air pollution, which is linked to respiratory and cardiovascular diseases. The disposal challenges of nuclear waste also pose risks to communities near power generation and waste storage sites ([Johnson, 2017](https://www.coursebb.com/2017/01/25/business-social-problems-data-center-power-consumption-cause/)).

